Project: Predicting F1 Race Winners and Podium Finishers
The goal of this project is to build and evaluate a machine learning model that predicts the winner of a Formula 1 Grand Prix. An advanced extension will be to predict which drivers will finish on the podium (Top 3). The project will leverage historical race data, qualifying performance, driver/team statistics, and tyre strategies, all sourced using the fastf1 library.

## Phase 1: Foundations and Data Acquisition (Weeks 1-5)
This initial phase focuses on setting up the project environment and gathering the raw data needed for analysis and modeling.

Week 1: Project Scaffolding & Environment Setup

Tasks: Define the project's scope and final objectives. Set up your Python environment (e.g., using Anaconda or venv). Install core libraries: fastf1, pandas, numpy, matplotlib, and seaborn. Initialize a Git repository to track your progress.

Goal: A functional development environment and a clear project plan.

Week 2: fastf1 Library Immersion

Tasks: Dive into the fastf1 documentation. Practice loading data from a single race weekend (e.g., results, qualifying, lap times). Configure the fastf1 cache to store downloaded data and speed up future requests.

Goal: Become comfortable with the basic functions of fastf1.

Week 3: Historical Data Harvesting (Race & Qualifying)

Tasks: Write a script to iterate through past seasons (e.g., 2018-2024). For each Grand Prix, download and save the final race results and qualifying results into separate CSV files.

Goal: A raw dataset of final race outcomes and starting grid positions.

Week 4: Expanding Data Collection

Tasks: Enhance your script to gather more contextual data for each race, including championship standings before the race, practice session results, and historical weather data (e.g., Rainfall, TrackTemp).

Goal: Enrich the dataset with variables that influence race performance.

Week 5: Data Aggregation and Cleaning

Tasks: Combine all the collected data into a single, master pandas DataFrame. Address missing values (e.g., for drivers who Did Not Finish - DNF), standardize data types (e.g., convert time intervals to seconds), and perform initial checks for errors.

Goal: A unified, clean dataset ready for exploration.

## Phase 2: Analysis and Feature Creation (Weeks 6-12)
This phase is about understanding the data, uncovering patterns, and engineering new features to improve model performance.

Week 6: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) - Part 1

Tasks: Perform descriptive statistics. Create initial visualizations to understand basic relationships, such as the correlation between qualifying position and finishing position or the distribution of wins by team.

Goal: First insights into the data's structure and key variables.

Week 7: EDA - Part 2

Tasks: Create more advanced visualizations. Analyze the impact of the starting grid, team performance across different circuits, and the effect of weather conditions on race outcomes.

Goal: Deeper understanding of the factors that determine race results.

Week 8: Introduction to Lap-by-Lap Data

Tasks: Using fastf1, select a few iconic races and analyze the lap-by-lap data. Plot driver lap times, compare tyre degradation, and visualize position changes throughout a race.

Goal: Understand in-race dynamics and how they can be quantified.

Week 9: Pre-Race Feature Engineering

Tasks: Create new features from existing data. Examples include Driver Form (average finishing position in the last 5 races), Team Form (average points in the last 5 races), and Qualifying Delta (time difference to the pole-sitter).

Goal: Engineer predictive variables that the model can learn from.

Week 10: Strategy-Based Feature Engineering

Tasks: Extract historical pit stop and tyre strategy data. Create features like Average Pit Stop Time per team and the most common tyre strategies used at a specific track.

Goal: Quantify the impact of team strategy on race outcomes.

Week 11: Feature Selection and Preprocessing

Tasks: Use techniques like correlation heatmaps to identify the most promising features. Prepare the data for modeling by scaling numerical features (StandardScaler) and encoding categorical features like circuit name (OneHotEncoder).

Goal: A final, model-ready dataset.

Week 12: Mid-Project Review

Tasks: Pause and review all progress. Consolidate your notebooks, document your EDA findings, and refine your feature engineering logic.

Goal: Ensure the project is on track and all previous steps are well-documented.

## Phase 3: Machine Learning Modeling and Evaluation (Weeks 13-19)
Here, you'll build, train, and rigorously test your predictive models.

Week 13: Building a Baseline Model

Tasks: Split your data into training and testing sets (e.g., train on 2018-2022, test on 2023-2024). Build a simple baseline model, like Logistic Regression, to establish a performance benchmark.

Goal: A simple model to compare all future, more complex models against.

Week 14: Advanced Modeling - Ensemble Methods

Tasks: Train more powerful models like a Random Forest or Gradient Boosting (e.g., XGBoost, LightGBM) classifier. These models are excellent at capturing complex, non-linear relationships in data.

Goal: Develop a high-performance predictive model.

Week 15: Hyperparameter Tuning

Tasks: Fine-tune your best-performing model. Use techniques like Grid Search or Randomized Search to find the optimal set of hyperparameters that maximize predictive accuracy.

Goal: Squeeze the maximum performance out of your chosen algorithm.

Week 16: Model Evaluation

Tasks: Evaluate your final model using metrics like Accuracy, Precision, Recall, and the F1-Score. Analyze a Confusion Matrix to see where your model is making correct and incorrect predictions.

Goal: A thorough and honest assessment of your model's performance.

Week 17: Predicting Podiums (Extension)

Tasks: Adapt your model for a multi-class classification problem (predicting 1st, 2nd, 3rd, or Other). Alternatively, build a model that outputs the probability of each driver finishing in the top 3.

Goal: Extend the project's scope and tackle a more challenging prediction task.

Week 18: Feature Importance and Model Interpretability

Tasks: Use techniques like SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) to understand why your model is making its predictions. Identify which features (e.g., qualifying position, driver form) are most influential.

Goal: Open the "black box" of the model and explain its decision-making process.

Week 19: Backtesting on a Full Season

Tasks: Simulate making predictions for each race of a season not used in training (e.g., the 2024 season). Track your model's accuracy race-by-race to see how it would have performed in a real-world scenario.

Goal: Validate the model's robustness and practical utility.

## Phase 4: Finalization and Presentation (Weeks 20-25)
The final phase involves documenting your work, creating a presentation, and potentially building a simple application to showcase your model.

Week 20: Building a Simple User Interface

Tasks: Create a simple front-end for your model using a framework like Streamlit or Flask. The app should allow a user to see the predictions for an upcoming race.

Goal: A tangible way to demonstrate your project to others.

Week 21: Project Documentation

Tasks: Write a comprehensive README.md file for your GitHub repository. Document your data sources, methodology, and how to run your code. Clean up and comment your code notebooks.

Goal: A well-documented, professional-quality project repository.

Week 22: Creating the Final Report/Presentation

Tasks: Create a slide deck or written report that tells the story of your project. Start with the problem statement, walk through your analysis and modeling process, and end with your results and conclusions.

Goal: A clear and compelling narrative of your project.

Week 23: Refining Visualizations and Storytelling

Tasks: Polish the charts and graphs for your presentation. Ensure your story is easy to follow and your key findings are highlighted effectively.

Goal: An engaging and professional presentation.

Week 24: Rehearsal and Feedback

Tasks: Rehearse your presentation. Get feedback from friends or colleagues and make final adjustments to your slides, report, and application.

Goal: A polished and confident final delivery.

Week 25: Final Presentation and Project Handoff

Tasks: Deliver your final presentation. Publish your project code to GitHub. Write a blog post or portfolio entry summarizing your work and key learnings.

Goal: Successful completion and showcasing of your F1 data science project. 🏎️💨







