Of course. Here's a revised data science project focused on determining optimal F1 race strategy, complete with an updated 25-week timeline.

Project: F1 Race Strategy Optimization Engine
The goal of this project is to build an analytical tool that recommends the optimal race strategy based on track characteristics and weather conditions. Instead of predicting a winner, this project focuses on modeling tyre degradation and simulating race outcomes to identify the fastest way to complete a Grand Prix, answering questions like: "Is a one-stop or two-stop strategy faster at Silverstone in warm, dry conditions?"

## Phase 1: Foundations and Strategy-Focused Data Acquisition (Weeks 1-5)
This phase is dedicated to setting up the project and gathering the specific, detailed data needed to analyze race strategy.

Week 1: Project Scaffolding & Environment Setup

Tasks: Define the new project scope: "To build a tool that recommends F1 race strategies based on track and weather." Set up your Python environment with fastf1, pandas, numpy, matplotlib, seaborn, and scikit-learn. Initialize a Git repository.

Goal: A functional development environment and a clear, strategy-focused project plan.

Week 2: fastf1 Deep Dive into Laps and Tyres

Tasks: Focus on the fastf1 functions for accessing lap-by-lap data. Practice loading tyre information (compound, stint length, tyre age) and pit stop data for a single race weekend.

Goal: Proficiency in extracting the core datasets required for strategy analysis.

Week 3: Historical Data Harvesting (Laps, Tyres, Pits)

Tasks: Write a script to iterate through past seasons (e.g., 2018-2024). For each race, download and save detailed lap-by-lap data, including the tyre compound used on each lap and all pit stop information.

Goal: A rich dataset of in-race actions and tyre usage.

Week 4: Harvesting Contextual Data (Weather & Track Info)

Tasks: Enhance your script to collect detailed weather data for each race session (Rainfall, TrackTemp, AirTemp). Manually research and add a track_type category for each circuit (e.g., 'High Degradation', 'Street Circuit', 'Power Circuit').

Goal: A dataset enriched with the primary external factors that influence strategy.

Week 5: Data Aggregation and Cleaning

Tasks: Merge all collected data into a unified pandas DataFrame. Clean the data by handling outliers (e.g., slow laps under a safety car), standardizing tyre compound names, and categorizing weather conditions.

Goal: A single, clean dataset optimized for strategy and degradation analysis.

## Phase 2: Analysis and Strategy-Based Feature Engineering (Weeks 6-12)
This phase focuses on understanding tyre behaviour and engineering features that numerically describe race strategy and performance.

Week 6: EDA - Tyre Compound Performance

Tasks: Analyze the raw pace difference between Soft, Medium, and Hard tyres at various circuits. Visualize the typical length of a tyre stint for each compound to understand their durability.

Goal: Initial insights into the fundamental trade-offs between tyre compounds.

Week 7: EDA - Tyre Degradation Analysis

Tasks: For several sample races, plot lap times versus the age of the tyres to visualize performance drop-off (degradation). Calculate a simple degradation metric for each stint (e.g., the slope of a line fitted to the lap times).

Goal: Quantify how tyre performance worsens over time.

Week 8: EDA - Impact of Weather and Track Type

Tasks: Compare degradation rates on the same track in different temperatures. Analyze how different track types affect tyre wear. For example, compare degradation at a high-wear circuit like Bahrain to a low-wear circuit like Monaco.

Goal: Understand how external conditions impact tyre behaviour.

Week 9: Feature Engineering - Quantifying Degradation

Tasks: Create a robust and reliable feature named degradation_rate for every tyre stint in the dataset. This will become the primary target for your machine learning model.

Goal: A precise, engineered target variable that captures tyre performance.

Week 10: Feature Engineering - Defining Strategy

Tasks: Create features that describe the race strategy itself. Examples include num_pit_stops and the sequence of tyres used (e.g., M-H for a one-stop or S-M-S for a two-stop).

Goal: Features that allow the model to understand strategic choices.

Week 11: Defining the "Optimal Strategy" Target

Tasks: For each historical race, identify the strategy used by the winning driver or the majority of the top 5 finishers. This will be used later to validate your final recommendations.

Goal: A benchmark for evaluating the success of your strategy tool.

Week 12: Mid-Project Review

Tasks: Consolidate your notebooks and document your analysis findings. Ensure your feature engineering logic is sound and well-documented before moving to the modeling phase.

Goal: A solid and well-documented foundation for the modeling stage.

## Phase 3: Modeling and Simulation (Weeks 13-19)
This is the core technical phase where you'll build a model to predict degradation and then use it to simulate and compare different race strategies.

Week 13: Building a Degradation Prediction Model

Tasks: Frame the problem as a regression task. Build a model (e.g., Gradient Boosting Regressor) to predict the degradation_rate based on features like track type, weather, and tyre compound.

Goal: A machine learning model that can forecast tyre wear under specific conditions.

Week 14: Hyperparameter Tuning and Model Refinement

Tasks: Use techniques like Grid Search to fine-tune your degradation model's hyperparameters, improving its predictive accuracy.

Goal: An optimized and highly accurate degradation model.

Week 15: Model Evaluation and Interpretation

Tasks: Evaluate the model's performance using metrics like Mean Absolute Error (MAE). Use SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) to interpret the model, identifying which factors (e.g., track temperature) are the biggest drivers of tyre degradation.

Goal: Confidence in your model's accuracy and an understanding of why it makes its predictions.

Week 16: Building a Basic Race Simulator

Tasks: Develop a Python script that uses your degradation model to simulate a full race distance. For a given strategy (e.g., "start on Medium, pit on lap 25 for Hard"), the simulator should calculate the total race time.

Goal: A functional engine that can turn a strategy into a predicted race time.

Week 17: Enhancing the Simulator

Tasks: Add more realism. Factor in the total time lost during a pit stop (around 20-25 seconds) and the performance difference between fresh and worn tyres (undercut/overcut potential).

Goal: A more accurate simulation that reflects real-world race dynamics.

Week 18: Developing the Strategy Recommender

Tasks: Write logic that allows the simulator to run multiple common strategies (e.g., all sensible one-stop and two-stop options) for a given race. The tool should then compare the total simulated race times and recommend the fastest one.

Goal: The core logic of your optimization tool.

Week 19: Backtesting the Recommender

Tasks: Run your recommender on historical races (e.g., the full 2023 season). Compare the strategy your tool suggests with the actual strategy used by the winning team. Analyze and understand any differences.

Goal: Validation of your tool's effectiveness against real-world outcomes.

## Phase 4: Finalization and Presentation (Weeks 20-25)
The final phase focuses on building a user-friendly interface for your tool and presenting your project.

Week 20: Building the Strategy Tool Interface

Tasks: Use a framework like Streamlit to build a simple, interactive web application. The UI should allow a user to select a race track and input weather conditions.

Goal: A user-friendly front-end for your strategy engine.

Week 21: Visualizing Strategy Recommendations

Tasks: Add visualizations to your Streamlit app. This could include a table comparing the top 3 strategies, or a graph showing the predicted lap times and pit stops for the optimal strategy.

Goal: An intuitive and visually appealing way to present the results.

Week 22: Project Documentation

Tasks: Write a thorough README.md file for your project on GitHub. Document your methodology for modeling degradation, how the simulator works, and instructions for running the app.

Goal: A professional, well-documented project repository.

Week 23: Creating the Final Presentation

Tasks: Create a slide deck that tells the story of your project. Explain the importance of race strategy, your analytical approach, and demo your final interactive tool.

Goal: A clear and compelling narrative of your work.

Week 24: Rehearsal and Feedback

Tasks: Practice your presentation and demo. Get feedback from others to refine your delivery and finalize all materials.

Goal: A polished and confident final presentation.

Week 25: Final Presentation and Project Completion

Tasks: Deliver your final presentation. Publish your project code and a link to the live Streamlit app on your portfolio or GitHub.

Goal: Successful completion and showcasing of your F1 strategy optimization engine. 🏁🔧








